 England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sharrott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Sherrard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sherrard","meanings":["English:","from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Shirard</i> (Old English <i>Scīrheard</i>, composed of the elements <i>scīr</i> ‘bright’ and <i>heard</i> ‘hard, bold’). Alternatively, the name may be a nickname deriving from Middle English <i>shir</i> (Old English <i>scīr</i>) ‘bright, fair’, with the addition of the Anglo-Norman French suffix <i>-ard</i>.","local pronunciation of   Sherwood  , especially perhaps in Leicestershire, Kent, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Sussex, and Yorkshire. It may also have been much confused with   Skerritt  . This name, or the name in 1 above, has been established in Ireland (Derry) since the 17th century, along with <i>Sherwood</i> (in most provinces)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":64,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":66,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Sharrott was born in 1505, in Norfolk, England. She married Samson Sharrot in 1524, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1575, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1505–1575":"1505–1575","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1532–1569":"1532–1569","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1524":"1524","1502":"1502","1532":"1532","1575":"1575","6 July 1569":"6. juuli 1569","1571":"1571","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1505–1575":"1505–1575","1502–Male":"1502–Kuollut","1532–1569":"1532–1569","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1524":"1524","1502":"1502","1532":"1532","1575":"1575","6 July 1569":"6. heinäkuuta 1569","1571":"1571","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1505–1575":"1505–1575","1502–Male":"1502–Décédé","1532